		- Name is given: Electron.
	- Conclusions
		- This particles has smaller mass than the smallest atom known! (hydrogen)!
		- This particles are faaar smaller than smallest atom known! (hydrogen)!



Other preliminaries (1890~1900)
	- X-Ray discovery
		- Cathod Ray Machine, again. But nicer this time.
		- 100kV high DC Voltage in vacuum tube
		- Electrons start from cathode, are accelerated by 100kV, and hit anode.
		- Placements of photographic plates around.
		- Emission of unknown type of radiation when electrons hit the anode (or the glass wall).
		- Detection of such radiation (photographic plates)
		- Call it: X-Rays =).
	- Further X-Ray study
		- Colimation of X-ray beam.
		- Beam placed in magnetic and electrostatic fields.
		- Conclusion: These X-Rays are neutral (non-charged).
	- Rutherford experiments (published 1899).
		- Fluorescence: Uranium exposed to photographic plate
		- Discovery of yet two unknown radiation. One positive charged, other negatively charged.
		- Call: Alpha Particles (the positive charged ones).
		- Call: Beta Particles (the negative charged ones).
	- Becquerel experiments (1900)
		- Experiment: Charge sign of a beta particle (its negative!)
		- Experiment: mass to charge ratio of beta particle
		- Experimental values: Same of the electrons!!!!
		- Conclusion: Perhaps beta particles are electrons?


Thomsom Atomic Model (1904)
	- JJ Thompson discovers the electron! (1897)
		- Physicist and chemist
		- He knew the current electromagnetic theory (Maxwell Equations).
	- Descoberta do Elétron (by JJ Thomsom)
		- Tubos de raios catódicos
		- Experiment: Ratio charge-mass of electron
		- Robert Milikan Experiments: Charge of electron
	- Motivation to Thomsom Atomic Theory
		- Electrons are negatively charged (as proved earlier).
		- Atoms are neutral! (as everyone knows).
		- The electron of cathode tube from thermoioni emission came from somewhere.....
		- Also, again, the electron from beta emission has to come from somewhere...
		- Later justifications
			- (1905) Remember: Photoelectric effect. The electron has to come from somewhere....
			- (1913) Remember: Compton Effect. The electron again has to come from somewhere....
			- Note: Low and Mid energy physics experiments seems to indicate there is an electron in the atom.
		- Measuring the estimated number of electrons in an atom. Roughly: chemcial atomic weight / 2.
	- Thomson atomic theory (1904)
		- Proposal: The atom is made of electrons
		- Problem: Electron has negative charge. Atom is wide known neutral
		- Proposal: The atom is made of electrons, spreaded in a positive mass/cloud/whatever
		- Math Model: Spherical distribution of positive charge (volumetric charge density).
		- Plum pudding model
	- Explicação de emissão de radiação usando modelo de Thomson
		- Radiação eletromagnética de objetos aquecidos (black body radiation)
		- Átomo com elétrons em niveis de energia maiores ==> Vibração de elétrons
		- Teoria eletromagnética clássica. Emissão de radiação de átomos.
		- Atomo em baixa energia: Életrons estáticos
		- Nota: Quantitative agreement is lacking.
	- Física do Modelo de Thomsom: The Hydrogen Atom
		- 1 electron inside a positive charge density
			- Warning: At the time, charge of positive cloud of hydrogen atom was not known.
		- Potencial eletrostático sofrido por elétron em Átomo de Thomsom.
			- Calc: Campo elétrico e potencial fora da densidade de carga positiva
			- Calc: Campo elétrico e potencial dentro da densidade de carga positiva. Lei de Gauss.
			- Calc: Força sofrida por elétron dentro da densidade de carga positiva.
		- Dinamica 1D do elétron no átomo de Thomsom
			- Calc: Equação diferencial do elétron
			- Note: Movimento harmonico simples sendo executado por elétron (passa pelo centro)
			- Calc: Frequencia e comprimento de onda (radiação eletromagnética emitida por vibração)
			- Aplicação numérica para átomo de hidrogenio. Comprimento de onda da radiação emitida
			- Note: Perda de energia por emissão de radiação (Larmor formula)
			- Note: Damped differential equation.
		- Dinamica 3D do elétron no átomo de Thomsom
			- Calc: Potencial efetivo
			- Calc: Órbita do Elétron
			- Calc: Energia de escape da região de densidade de carga
			- Calc: Energia de ionização
			- Calc: Momento angular
		- Calc: Energia de Ionização do àtomo de Hidrogenio
		- Calc: Frequencia de emissão de radiação do Átomo de Thomsom
		- Calc: Wavelenth da emissão de radiação
		- Calc: Superposição de oscilações harmonicas nos eixos tridimensionais do àtomo de Thomsom
		- Calc: Frequencia e comprimento de onda de emissão de radiação de Átomo de Thomsom tridimensional
		- Note: Frequencia/wavelength depende do raio do átomo
		- Note: Electron will spiral in until become static at center (lowest energy state).
		- Calc: Intensidade da radiação emitida com respeito ao tempo.
		- Calc: Tempo da emissão de radiação (em função of initial kinetic energy)
		- Note: Disagrees with experiment... =(.
	- Explanations
		- Explains ionization of neutral atoms by strong electric fields (high voltages) (say... 100kV)
		- Explains where the electron comes from, in several other experiments.
	- Perguntas não respondidas do modelo de Thomsom
		- A densidade de carga positiva deve ser igual à massa do átomo (electrons barely has mass). How can it be?
		- O que exatamente é essa densidade de carga positiva?


Rutherford-Royds Experiment (1907)
	- Authors: Ernest Rtheford, Thomas Royds.
	- Objective: What are Alpha Rays?
	- Experimental Set-Up
		- Source of Alpha Rays in vacuum sealed compartment
		- Very thin layer of glass inside.
	- The experiment
		- Alpha rays hit the thin layer of glass
		- Trapping alpha particles in the glass (in large numbers I shall add)
		- To cause electric spark inside the vacuum tube (or maybe cathod rays).
		- Electrons combined with the positive alpha particles and combined. Gas is formed.
		- Studying emission spetrum of the produced gas. ITS HELIUM!
	- The conclusion
		- Alpha particles are simply ionized atoms of helium.
		- Note: Qualitatevely at least, Thomsom Atomic Model is again proven correct.


Modelo Atomico de Rutherford (1911)
	- Warning: Physics (big calcs) starts here. Take your sits. Prepare yourselves. =).
	- Events leading to discovery...
		- Era uma vez dois alunos de Rutherford desocupados
		- Rutheford: Go measure the scattering of alpha particles by gold foil! (1909)
		- Analysis of experimental data made by Rutherford (1911)
	- Description of Rutherford's experimental equipment
		- Alpha particle spontaneously emitted by radioactive source
		- Alpha particle: Doubly ionized (thomsom) atom of helium.
		- Colimation of the alpha beam.
		- Beam targeting thin foil of a given substance.
		- Microscope with ZnS crystal. Alpha particle hit in ZnS: light flash.
		- Measured quantity: Number of light flashes per unit time in given scattering angle.
	- Espalhamento de particulas alpha por electron
		- Conservação do momentum linear
		- Conservação da energia cinética (colisão perfeitamente elástica)
		- Calc: Deflexão de particula alpha causada por um elétron
		- Numerical calc: Angulo de deflexão
		- Note: Ridiculously small angle.
	- Espalhamento de particulas alpha na região positiva
		- TODO.
	- TODO: Full cross-sectional calculations with Thomsom potential of atom. Note it won't match. Verify if we need to go relativistic.
	- TODO: Inverse scattering problem for given angular distribution of alpha particles. Find inverse potential.
	- TODO: Calculate differential cross section and total cross section of inverse potential.
	- TODO: Based on the calculations, propose the rutheford model
		- TODO: qualitaively explain emission of radiation
		- TODO: Show how to calculate charge of nucleous. Show charge / elmentary charge equals chemical atomic number.
		- TODO: Limits of the size of the atomic nucleous
	- Nuclear Penetration
		- Calc: Distancia de aproximação máxima da particula alpha (head on collision)
		- Correção do espalhamento de rutheford para átomos leves (no calc).
		- Desvios da predição de espalhamento de Rutheford para átomos leves.
		- Estimation: Tamanho do núcleo do átomo, baseado nos desvios do espalhamento de Rutheford.
	- Visão qualitativa do modelo de Rutherford
		- Átomo tem massa concentrado no nucleo de dimensões na ordem de 10^-14 m.
		- Nucleo tem carga Ze, Z numero atômico, e carga elementar do elétron.
		- Eletrons estão do lado de fora, empty space. Z eletrons with charge Ze.
		- Elétrons orbitam nucleo atomico.
		- Emissão de radiação da orbita eletrônica, e subsequente colapso do átomo.
		- Átomos de Rutheford são instáveis. Um dia se desintegra. Hm.. We need numbers.
	- Rutherford Hydrogen Atom
		- Calc: Ionization Energy of the hydrogen (Comparisom with thomsom, rutheford and experimental value).
		- Calc: Potencial e campo eletrico sofrido pelo eletron
		- Calc: Frequencia do eletron
		- Calc: Energia da orbita do eletron
		- Calc: Estabilidade to átomo de hidrogenio. 
		- Calc: Tempo para colapso do átomo de hidrogenio
		- Note: Tempo de vida do hidrogenio is in HUUUUGE disagrement of real life.
	- Estability of all atoms
		- Remmeber: Earshall Theorem
		- Calc: Estimated Time for atomic collapse.
		- Question: Can we justify this by saying that the colapsed atom is what exists in real world?
	- Conclusions
		- ALL atoms are unstable and shouldn't exist! What a nice model.....
		- Nevertheless, this atomic model is in best agreement with experiments so far (ie, less-worse agreement).


Modelo Atomico de Bohr (1913).
	- Motivation of the Bohr Atom
		- Priority Number 01: To keep the Rutheford atom from collapsing.
		- Planck Quantization formula: E = hf.
		- Borrowing the photon concept from Einstein (1905).
	- Bohr's Reasoning
		- If Energy can be quantized, why not angular momentum?
		- Assume: Quantization of angular momentum: L = n hbar (hbar proportionality constant) (to be determined later).
		- Note: if n=0, the atom is collapsed. Hence, exclude that possibility
		- Note: n=1 is the smallestp ossible value.
		- Note: Eletron cannot emit radiation: n=1 is minimum. If it does, L is not quantized (contradiction to hypothesis).
	- Quantization of Angular momentum
		- Recall: E = hf, and f = 1/T.
		- Intuition for L = nh/2pi (hbar = h/2pi).
		- TODO: More rigorous calculation for quantization of angular momentum.
	- Bohr's Atomic Model
		- Several electrons in circular orbit around the nucleous (charge Ze).
		- Calc: Centrifugal Force equals potential electrostatic energy
		- Calc: Application of quantization of angular momentum
		- Calc: The radius of the atoms (bohr radius)
		- Calc: The energy of the atoms (bohr energy) (from potential energy).
		- Note: Energy, radius and orbits are quantized.
		- Camadas Atomicas: K, L, M, N, ...
	- Emissão de Radiação de átomos
		- Electrons passing de uma camada para outra
		- Emission of a photon of light by delta E = hf (Einstein sense of photon)
		- Frequency of atomic emission.
		- Spectrum of atoms
	- Bohr's Hydrogen Atom
		- Calc: Radius of the hydrogen atom
		- Calc: Energy Levels of the Hydrogen atom
		- Calc: Ionization energy of the hydrogen atom
		- Calc: Spectral Lines of the hydrogen atom.
		- Calc: Rydberg constant from the spectral lines.
		- Calc: Reproduction of Balmer Formula
		- Note: FULL agreemental with the highly-precisely-already-measured rydberg constant.
		- Note: FULL experimental agreement with Balmer Spectral Sequence
		- Note: Experimental agreement of predicted ionization energy
		- FANTASTIC! Everything is in experimental agreement!! EVERYTHING!!!!
	- Bohr's Helium Atom
		- Calc: Radius of the helium atom
		- Calc: Energy levels of the helium atom
		- Calc: Ionization energy of helium (experimental: -24.587eV)
		- Calc: Percentage of error from Bohr's ionization energy and experimental value.
		- Note: BAAAD disagreeement.
		- Experimental spectral lines in huuge disagrement as well.
	- Alkaline Metals
		- Calc: Ionization energy for Lithium using bohr (experimental: -520.2 kJ/mol)
		- Calc: Ionization energy for sodium using bohr (experimental: -496kJ/mol)
		- Calc: Percentage of error from Bohr's ionization energy and experimental value.
		- Note: Hmm.. not bad..
		- Question: Why Bohr's atom model works for alkaline metals?
	- Conclusions
		- Explains hydrogen in amazing detail and correctness.
		- Fails to explain the helium. Fails all other atoms as well. 
		- Reason: Didn't consider repulsion between electrons!
		- Only works for hydrogen!


